Lists.name: Ask for
Lists.meaning: To request or demand something
example: She asked for help when she couldn't figure it out on her own.
He's always asking for favors but never returns them.
I asked for a refund when the product arrived damaged.
The protesters are asking for changes to the legislation.
They asked for clarification on the instructions.

Lists.name: Blow up
Lists.meaning: To explode or burst suddenly
example: The fireworks blew up in the sky.
The bomb blew up outside the building.
The engine blew up while he was driving.
The microwave blew up when she turned it on.
The gas tank blew up in the accident.

Lists.name: mess up
Lists.meaning: To make a mistake or to cause something to fail or become disordered
example: He always messes up his room before guests come over.
I'm worried I'll mess up the presentation tomorrow.
the new employee kept messing up the orders

Lists.name: step in
Lists.meaning: To intervene or become involved in a situation, often to help or take control
example: When the argument got heated, I had to step in and calm everyone down.
The teacher stepped in to stop the bullying.
I don't want to step in unless absolutely necessary.

Lists.name: unhinge
Lists.meaning: To disturb mentally or emotionally, causing someone to become mentally unbalanced or emotionally upset.
example: The tragic news of her friend's death completely unhinged her.
His constant criticism began to unhinge her confidence.
Witnessing the accident unhinged him for days afterward.

Lists.name: slovenly
Lists.meaning: Messy and dirty; careless; excessively casual.
example: His slovenly appearance made a bad impression at the interview.
The room was in a slovenly state, with clothes and papers scattered everywhere
She was criticized for her slovenly work habits.

Lists.name: bury
Lists.meaning:
A burrow.
To ritualistically inter in a grave or tomb.
To place in the ground.
To hide or conceal as if by covering with earth or another substance.
To suppress and hide away in one's mind.
To put an end to; to abandon.
To score a goal.
To kill or murder.
To render imperceptible by other, more prominent stimuli; drown out.
example: vocals buried in the mix
bury a bone;  bury the embers
she buried her face in the pillow;  they buried us in paperwork
secrets kept buried; she buried her shame and put on a smiling face.

Lists.name: hesitate
Lists.meaning:
To stop or pause respecting decision or action; to be in suspense or uncertainty as to a determination.
To stammer; to falter in speaking.
To utter with hesitation or to intimate by a reluctant manner.
example: He hesitated whether to accept the offer or not; men often hesitate in forming a judgment.

Lists.name: wear
Lists.meaning:
To have clothing, accessories, or other items on one's body.
The act of wearing something; clothing suitable for a particular purpose or occasion.
example: He's wearing some nice pants today.  She wore her medals with pride.  Please wear your seatbelt.  Can you wear makeup and sunscreen at the same time?  He was wearing his lunch after tripping and falling into the buffet.
He wears eyeglasses.  She wears her hair in braids.
Her high pitched voice is really wearing on me lately.

Lists.name: befall
Lists.meaning: To happen to someone, especially something bad or unfortunate.
example: A great tragedy befell the village during the storm.
At dusk an unusual calm befalls the wetlands.
Temptation befell me.

Lists.name: belittle
Lists.meaning: To make someone or something seem less important or less worthy of respect.
example: He belittles her achievements, making her feel undervalued.
Don't belittle your colleagues.
The manager belittles his team, which affects their morale.
She often belittles her own efforts, not realizing how much she contributes.

Lists.name: concern
Lists.meaning: Matters that cause worry, anxiety, or interest
example: I’m concerned that she’s becoming an alcoholic.
A good prince concerns himself in the happiness of his subjects.
Judy's eyes filled with concern as she listened to the news report.

Lists.name: meld
Lists.meaning: To blend or combine together.
example: The chef melded different flavors to create a unique dish.
Their voices melded harmoniously in the choir.
The new policy melds traditional methods with modern technology.

Lists.name: swoop in
Lists.meaning: To arrive quickly and unexpectedly in a particular place, especially in order to take advantage of an opportunity or to deal with a situation.
example: The company swooped in with a better offer just as he was about to sign the contract with his current employer.
The police swooped in and arrested the suspects.
The hawk swooped in and caught the mouse.

Lists.name: wax
Lists.meaning: To increase gradually in size, strength, or intensity.
example: The moon waxes and wanes in a cycle.
Her enthusiasm for the project waxed as it progressed.

Lists.name: fees
Lists.meaning: Payments made for professional services, transactions, or privileges.
example: The lawyer's fees were quite high for handling the case.
There are additional fees for late payments.
He paid the membership fees to join the club.

Lists.name: ramble
Lists.meaning:
To talk or write at length in a confused or inconsequential way.
To move about or wander aimlessly or without any clear direction.
example: He rambled on about his travels, jumping from one story to another.
The path through the forest rambled on for miles.
His speech rambled, making it difficult to follow his main points.

Lists.name: wary
Lists.meaning: Feeling or showing caution about possible dangers or problems.
example: She was wary of strangers offering help.
He was wary of investing in the new venture.
The cat was wary of the new dog in the house.

Lists.name: deceptive
Lists.meaning: Giving an appearance or impression different from the true one; misleading.
example: The advertisement was deceptive and did not show the true quality of the product.
His calm demeanor was deceptive, hiding his nervousness.

Lists.name: dig up
Lists.meaning:
Unearthed or excavated something from the ground.
Discovered or found information, often after a thorough search.
example: The archaeologists dug up ancient artifacts at the site.
The reporter dug up some old records about the politician's past.

Lists.name: warmed up
Lists.meaning:
Prepared for physical activity by exercising or stretching beforehand
Became more enthusiastic, comfortable, or engaged in an activity or conversation..
example: The athletes warmed up before the race.
She warmed up to the idea after thinking about it for a while.

Lists.name: ward
Lists.meaning:
A separate room in a hospital, typically one allocated to a particular type of patient (noun).
A person, especially a minor, who is under the protection and care of a guardian or court (noun).
To guard or protect (verb, usually used with "off" as in "ward off").
example: She was admitted to the pediatric ward for treatment (noun).
The orphan became a ward of the state
He tried to ward off the attacker with a stick

Lists.name: plug
Lists.meaning:
Noun: A device for making an electrical connection between an appliance and a power supply.
Noun: A piece used to block a hole or fill a gap.
Verb: To fill a hole or gap.
Verb: To mention or promote something publicly
example: Make sure to put the plug into the socket.
She had to plug the leak in the boat.
The author plugged his new book during the interview.

Lists.name: whip out
Lists.meaning: to take out or produce something quickly and suddenly
example: He whipped out his phone to capture the moment.
She whipped out a notebook from her bag and started taking notes

Lists.name: dangle
Lists.meaning:
Verb: Hanging or swinging loosely.
Adjective: Hanging or swinging freely.
example: The keys were dangling from his belt
She was dangling her feet off the edge of the dock

Lists.name: ceiling
Lists.meaning:
Noun: The upper interior surface of a room.
Noun: An upper limit set on prices, wages, or other variables.
Noun (Aviation): The maximum altitude that an aircraft can reach under specific conditions.
example: The chandelier was hanging from the ceiling.
There is a ceiling on the amount of rent landlords can charge.

Lists.name: advice
Lists.meaning: hikjik
example: huijik

Lists.name: Blow over
Lists.meaning: To pass or be forgotten with little or no consequence
example: The argument blew over after a few days.
The scandal eventually blew over and was forgotten.
The storm blew over without causing much damage.
Hopefully, this issue will blow over soon.
He hoped that the incident would blow over before anyone noticed.

Lists.name: Investigate into
Lists.meaning: To inquire into or examine something thoroughly, typically to uncover facts or solve a problem
example: She investigated into the cause of the fire.
They investigated into the allegations of corruption.
He investigated into the disappearance of the missing person.
The authorities investigated into the company's financial irregularities.
We need to investigate into the matter before drawing conclusions.

Lists.name: threat
Lists.meaning:
A statement or indication of an intention to inflict pain, harm, or damage.
A person or thing likely to cause damage or danger.
example: The email contained a threat to her safety.
Climate change is a significant threat to biodiversity.

Lists.name: Will someone keep
Lists.meaning: a question that wonder if someone keep doing an action in the future
example: will he keep eating

Lists.name: stir up trouble
Lists.meaning: to increase the trouble between to or more people
example: i dont want to stir up trouble between you and your wife

Lists.name: fund
Lists.meaning: A sum of money saved or made available for a particular purpose
example: The government allocated funds for education.
She set up a fund to help local charities.
The company's pension fund provides retirement benefits to employees.

Lists.name: right up
Lists.meaning:
often used to indicate something that aligns perfectly with someone's preferences or location.
Perfectly suited to someone's tastes or interests.
All the way to a specific point or time.
example: They worked right up to the deadline.
This new book on medieval history is right up your alley
The new science fiction movie is right up my alley; I love films like that.

Lists.name: way outta line
Lists.meaning: Extremely inappropriate or unacceptable behavior; exceeding the limits of what is considered reasonable or acceptable.
example: His comments were way outta line
She crossed the line when she said that, it was way outta line

Lists.name: Up for graps
Lists.meaning: Available for anyone to take or win; not yet claimed or settled.
example: The last slice of pizza is up for grabs.
The promotion was up for grabs, and she decided to apply.
The championship title will be up for grabs at the final game.

Lists.name: get a head start
Lists.meaning: To begin an activity or task earlier than others, giving oneself an advantage.
example: If we leave now, we can get a head start on traffic.
She got a head start on her homework over the weekend.
They will get a head start on the project by starting today.

Lists.name: cut loose
Lists.meaning: To release or set someone free, either literally (e.g., from physical restraint) or figuratively (e.g., from a job, responsibility, or relationship).
example: They decide to cut him loose from the project due to his lack of commitment
The manager cut him loose after repeated warnings.
She will cut him loose if he continues to underperform.

Lists.name: rely
Lists.meaning: (with on or upon, formerly also with in) to trust; to have confidence in; to depend.
example: She is relying on her friends for emotional support during this difficult time.
They are relying on the weather to stay dry for their outdoor event.
He has been relying on his savings since losing his job.

Lists.name: shut down
Lists.meaning:
To close, terminate, or end.
To turn off or stop.
To emotionally withdraw into oneself as a defense mechanism; to block out external stressors.
(auto racing, car culture) To pass (another vehicle), especially quickly.
example: The factory shut down due to financial losses.
They had to shut down the power plant for maintenance.
The company decided to shut down its operations in the region.

Lists.name: drop out
Lists.meaning:
To withdraw or quit from an activity, school, course, or competition.
To abandon or discontinue participation in something
example: He decided to drop out of college and pursue a career in music
Many students drop out of school due to financial difficulties.
She dropped out of the race after injuring her ankle.

Lists.name: hurdle
Lists.meaning:
As a Noun:

Meaning:

An obstacle or barrier that must be overcome to achieve a goal.
A problem or difficulty that must be dealt with.

As a Verb:

Meaning:

To jump over an obstacle, especially in a race.
To overcome or deal with a difficulty or obstacle.
example: She faced many hurdles on her path to success.
Lack of funding is a major hurdle for the project.
Overcoming language barriers was a significant hurdle for the international team.

Lists.name: delighted
Lists.meaning: Feeling or showing great pleasure, satisfaction, or joy.
example: She was delighted with the surprise birthday party.
The children were delighted to see the circus.
He was delighted by the unexpected gift from his friend.

Lists.name: plateau
Lists.meaning:
To reach a stable level after a period of growth or progress.
To stop increasing or improving and remain at the same level.
example: After months of rapid growth, sales have plateaued.
Her progress in learning the piano has plateaued recently.
The company's profits plateaued in the third quarter.

Lists.name: merely
Lists.meaning: Just; only; used to emphasize that something is not large, important, or significant.
example: He was merely a child when he moved to the new country
It's not merely a question of money; it's a matter of principle.
She merely nodded in response.

Lists.name: give out
Lists.meaning:
To distribute or hand out something to others.
To emit or release something, such as light, sound, or energy.
To announce or broadcast information.
(Intransitive) To cease functioning or become exhausted.
example: The teacher gave out the assignments to the students.
The old heater finally gave out a steady warmth.
They gave out the results of the competition over the loudspeaker.

Lists.name: shrug off
Lists.meaning:
To dismiss or ignore something, especially a problem or criticism, as unimportant or irrelevant.
To recover quickly from an illness, injury, or negative experience
example: He tried to shrug off the criticism and focus on his work.
She shrugged off the cold and went to work anyway.
Despite the setback, the team managed to shrug off their disappointment and win the next game.

Lists.name: open up
Lists.meaning:
To make something accessible or available.
To become willing to talk about personal thoughts and feelings.
To start or establish a new business or venture.
To create opportunities or possibilities.
example: The new highway will open up the region to more tourism.
She finally opened up about her struggles to her best friend.
They decided to open up a coffee shop in the downtown area.

Lists.name: core
Lists.meaning:
The central or most important part of something.
The central part of a fruit, containing the seeds.
A central, foundational part of a system, organization, or concept.

As a Verb:

Meaning:

To remove the central part of a fruit.
Examples:
example: The core of the Earth is composed of molten rock.
She sliced the apple and removed the core.
Trust is at the core of a strong relationship.

Lists.name: board
Lists.meaning:
Wider in extent or range.
Covering a wider scope or more general.
Having a wide range of different aspects or elements.
example: The river is much broader here than upstream.
The new curriculum offers a broader range of subjects for students.
We need to take a broader view of the issue to find a comprehensive solution

Lists.name: embody
Lists.meaning:
To represent or express something abstract in tangible form.
To include or contain something as a constituent part.
To be an example of a particular quality or idea.
example: The statue embodies the spirit of freedom.
Her actions embody the values of our community.
The new policy embodies the government's commitment to environmental sustainability.

Lists.name: wipe out
Lists.meaning:
To completely destroy or eliminate something.
To cause a person or group to suffer a severe defeat or loss.
To remove or erase something completely.
example: The tsunami wiped out entire villages along the coast.
The stock market crash wiped out their savings.
The disease wiped out entire populations in the past.

Lists.name: raging
Lists.meaning:
Characterized by violent or uncontrollable anger, emotions, or actions.
Marked by intense or widespread activity or movement.
example: The raging bull charged at the matador.
Her eyes showed a raging fury at the betrayal.
The river turned into a raging torrent after the heavy rainfall.

Lists.name: thriving
Lists.meaning: Prosperous and growing; flourishing.
example: The city's economy is thriving due to new investments.
The garden is thriving thanks to regular watering and care.
Despite the challenges, their business is thriving.

Lists.name: scorching
Lists.meaning: Extremely hot; burning or searing.
example: The scorching sun made it difficult to stay outside for long.
We had to wait until evening to go for a walk because of the scorching heat.
The desert experienced scorching temperatures during the day.

Lists.name: step up
Lists.meaning:
To increase the amount, speed, or intensity of something.
To take action or responsibility, especially when others are hesitant to do so.
To come forward or volunteer for a role or task.
example: The company plans to step up production to meet the high demand.

Lists.name: settler
Lists.meaning: People who move to a new area or country to live and establish a community, often in a region that is sparsely populated or uninhabited.
example: The early settlers faced many hardships in the New World.
The settlers built homes and farms in the remote valley.
European settlers arrived in America seeking freedom and land.

Lists.name: scooched over
Lists.meaning: To move a short distance, often to make space for someone or something else
example: She scooched over to make room for her friend on the bench.
He scooched over so that I could sit next to him.
They scooched over a bit to give the new student some space.

Lists.name: toss
Lists.meaning:
As a Verb:

Meaning:

To throw something lightly or casually.
To throw something up in the air, especially to mix ingredients or to determine an outcome.
To move or stir about restlessly.

As a Noun:

Meaning:

An act of throwing something lightly or casually.
A sudden or quick movement.
A throw or flip to decide something by chance.
example: She tossed the ball to her friend.
The chef tossed the salad before serving it.
He tossed the coin to decide who would go first.

Lists.name: slip past
Lists.meaning:
To move or pass by someone or something quietly or unnoticed.
To avoid detection or capture by moving stealthily or quickly.
example: The spy managed to slip past the guards undetected.
She tried to slip past her parents to avoid their questions.
I nearly missed the deadline, but I managed to slip past it just in time.

Lists.name: slip
Lists.meaning:
As a Verb:

Meaning:

To slide unintentionally for a short distance, typically losing one's balance or footing.
To move quietly and smoothly, often to avoid being noticed.
To pass or go by smoothly or easily.
To make a small mistake.
example: Be careful not to slip on the icy pavement
She slipped out of the room without anyone noticing.
Time seems to slip away when you're having fun.

Lists.name: gist
Lists.meaning: The main or essential part of a matter; the essence or central idea.
example: She didn't go into details but gave me the gist of the story
I missed the beginning of the meeting, but I got the gist of what was discussed.
The gist of his argument was that we need to invest more in renewable energy.

Lists.name: pawn off
Lists.meaning:
To get rid of or dispose of something, especially by tricking someone into accepting it.
To sell or trade something of little value or significance
example: He tried to pawn off his old computer as a high-end model.
She pawned off her duties to a coworker who didn't realize how tedious they were.

Lists.name: grueling
Lists.meaning: Extremely tiring and demanding; requiring a lot of effort and endurance.
example: The marathon was a grueling test of endurance.
She faced a grueling schedule at work this week.

Lists.name: choppet up
Lists.meaning: Cut into small pieces.
example: She chopped up the vegetables for the stew.
The meat was chopped up into small cubes.

Lists.name: dread
Lists.meaning:
To anticipate with great apprehension or fear.
A strong feeling of fear or apprehension
example: She dreaded the thought of speaking in public.
The dread of failure kept him awake at night.

Lists.name: stifling
Lists.meaning:
Very hot and causing difficulties in breathing; suffocating (adjective).
Making one feel constrained or oppressed (adjective).
example: The room was stifling due to the lack of ventilation
The stifling rules of the institution made it difficult for students to express themselves

Lists.name: pity
Lists.meaning: Characterized by a feeling of pity for oneself, often accompanied by a sense of victimhood or emotional indulgence.
example: He was in a self-pitying mood after losing the game.
Their self-pitying complaints annoyed everyone around them.

Lists.name: hectic
Lists.meaning: Full of incessant or frantic activity.
example: The holiday season is always hectic with so many events to attend.
She had a hectic day at the office with back-to-back meetings.

Lists.name: dilapidated
Lists.meaning: In a state of disrepair or ruin as a result of age or neglect.
example: The dilapidated house had been abandoned for years and was falling apart.
The old barn looked dilapidated, with its roof caving in and walls crumbling.
This man sold me his house without be aware that house was dilapidated.

Lists.name: scoff
Lists.meaning:
1. To speak to someone or about something in a scornfully derisive or mocking way (verb).
2. An expression of scornful derision (noun).
example: He scoffed at the idea of going to the party (verb).
Her suggestion was met with scoffs from her colleagues (noun).

Lists.name: rile up
Lists.meaning:
1. The unfair decision riled up the entire team.
2. She gets riled up every time she talks about politics.
example: The unfair decision riled up the entire team.
She gets riled up every time she talks about politics.

Lists.name: onwards
Lists.meaning:
1. In a continuing forward direction; ahead.
2. From a particular time forward.
example: We traveled onwards, eager to reach our destination.
From this day onwards, I promise to work harder.

Lists.name: fond
Lists.meaning:
1. Having an affection or liking for something or someone.
2. Affectionate and loving.
example: He has fond memories of his childhood.
She is very fond of her little brother.

Lists.name: enraged
Lists.meaning: Very angry; filled with rage
example: The unfair verdict left the crowd enraged
The constant delays enraged the passengers

Lists.name: compelling
Lists.meaning:
1. Evoking interest, attention, or admiration in a powerful and irresistible way.
2. Capable of causing someone to believe or agree.
example: The novel had a compelling storyline that kept readers hooked until the end.
Her argument was so compelling that everyone in the room agreed with her.

Lists.name: utter
Lists.meaning:
1. To speak or pronounce something.
2. Complete; absolute.
example: She uttered a few words of gratitude.
The situation was utter chaos.

Lists.name: swallow
Lists.meaning:
1. To cause or allow something to pass down the throat (verb).
2. To take in or accept something, especially difficult or unpleasant (verb).
3. A small bird with pointed wings and a forked tail (noun).
example: She took a sip of water and tried to swallow the pill.
He had to swallow his pride and apologize.
We saw a swallow building its nest under the eaves of the house.

Lists.name: fray
Lists.meaning: A situation of intense activity, typically one involving conflict or aggression; a state of disorder or tumult.
example: The protest turned into a fray between the demonstrators and the police.
There were multiple frays erupting throughout the city during the unrest.

Lists.name: sight
Lists.meaning: The faculty or power of seeing; a thing that one sees or that can be seen.
example: The sight of the sunset took my breath away.
The tourists marveled at the sights of the city.

Lists.name: flaw
Lists.meaning: A mark, blemish, or imperfection that mars a substance or object; a fault or weakness in a person's character or an argument.
example: The diamond had a small flaw that reduced its value.
Every plan has its flaws, but we can still make it work.

Lists.name: stubborn
Lists.meaning: Having or showing determination not to change one's attitude or position on something, especially in spite of good arguments or reasons to do so.
example: She is too stubborn to admit she was wrong.
The stubborn students refused to follow the new rules.

Lists.name: Thrill
Lists.meaning: Extremely excited or happy.
example: She was thrilled to hear about her promotion.
The children were thrilled by the magic show.

Lists.name: rod
Lists.meaning:
Noun: A thin, straight bar, especially of wood or metal.
Noun (Fishing): A long, slender pole used for fishing.
Noun: A unit of measurement equal to 5.5 yards or 16.5 feet.
Noun: A symbolic staff or scepter representing authority or power.
example: He used a rod to prop up the tent.
She caught a big fish using her new fishing rod.

Lists.name: wrap up
Lists.meaning: To finish or complete something, especially an activity or task.
example: We need to wrap up the meeting soon.
They wrapped up the project ahead of schedule.
I will wrap up my work before I leave for vacation.

Lists.name: frown
Lists.meaning:
To furrow one's eyebrows in an expression of displeasure, disapproval, or concentration.
An expression on the face in which the eyebrows are furrowed, typically indicating displeasure or concentration.
example: She frowned when she heard the bad news
He frowned at the messy room before cleaning it
They will frown upon such behavior if it continues.

Lists.name: bulge
Lists.meaning:
The act of swelling or protruding outward.
Swelling outwards; protruding in a rounded shape.
example: He noticed a bulging vein on his arm
The bulging eyes of the fish were quite prominent.

Lists.name: linger
Lists.meaning:
To stay or remain in a place or situation, especially as if unwilling to depart or not easily able to do so; to loiter.
To remain alive or existent although still proceeding toward death or extinction; to die gradually.
(often followed by on) To consider or contemplate for a period of time; to engage in analytic thinking or discussion.
example: She felt a lingering sadness after the farewell.
The lingering doubts kept him from making a decision.

Lists.name: wire
Lists.meaning: A thin, flexible thread of metal (usually aluminum or copper) used for conducting electricity or telecommunications.
example: The electrician fixed the problem with a new wire.

Lists.name: push further
Lists.meaning: To continue to advance or progress with more effort or determination; to extend or increase the extent of something.
example: He pushes further into the dense forest despite the warnings.
She pushed further into her studies to achieve her goals
They will push further to meet the project's deadline.

Lists.name: slip away
Lists.meaning: To leave quietly or secretly; to gradually disappear or become less noticeable.
example: She slips away from the party without saying goodbye.
He slipped away before anyone noticed he was gone.

Lists.name: slack
Lists.meaning: Not tight, taut, or firm; loose; lacking in activity or diligence.
example: the rope was slack and needed tightening
his slacks efforts were not enought to pass the exam

Lists.name: corpse
Lists.meaning: A dead body, especially of a human being.
example: The detectives found the corpse in an abandoned building.
The morgue was filled with unclaimed corpses.

Lists.name: lay
Lists.meaning:
Arrangement or relationship; layout.
A share of the profits in a business.
A lyrical, narrative poem written in octosyllabic couplets that often deals with tales of adventure and romance.
The direction a rope is twisted.
A casual sexual partner.
An act of sexual intercourse.
A plan; a scheme.
(uncountable) the laying of eggs.
A layer.
To place down in a position of rest, or in a horizontal position.
To cause to subside or abate.
To prepare (a plan, project etc.); to set out, establish (a law, principle).
To install certain building materials, laying one thing on top of another.
To produce and deposit an egg.
To bet (that something is or is not the case).
To deposit (a stake) as a wager; to stake; to risk.
To have sex with.
To take a position; to come or go.
To state; to allege.
To point; to aim.
(ropemaking) To put the strands of (a rope, a cable, etc.) in their proper places and twist or unite them.
To place and arrange (pages) for a form upon the imposing stone.
To place (new type) properly in the cases.
To apply; to put.
To impose (a burden, punishment, command, tax, etc.).
To impute; to charge; to allege.
To present or offer.
example: Did dinosaurs lay their eggs in a nest?
the lay of the land
to lay a cable or rope

Lists.name: toss aside
Lists.meaning: To discard or throw something away, often casually or carelessly.
example: She tossed aside the old magazines cluttering the table.
He felt hurt when his ideas were simply tossed aside during the meeting.

Lists.name: fang
Lists.meaning: A long, sharp tooth, typically one belonging to a carnivorous animal such as a snake, dog, or wolf.
example: The wolf bared its fangs and growled.
The snake's fangs are used to inject venom into its prey.

Lists.name: burst out
Lists.meaning:
To suddenly and forcefully come out or emerge.

To suddenly start doing something, such as laughing or crying.
example: The fireworks were bursting out in a magnificent display.
She couldn't hold back her emotions and burst out laughing.

Lists.name: squishy
Lists.meaning:
Soft and Yielding:
Easily deformed or flattened when squeezed or pressed.
Having a texture that gives way under pressure.
example: "The pillow was so squishy that it molded perfectly to her head."
"The baby's squishy cheeks were irresistible to pinch."
"The squishy mud made it difficult to walk through the field."

Lists.name: outdo
Lists.meaning:
To surpass or exceed someone or something in performance, achievement, or quality.
To do better than someone else in a competitive situation.
example: "She always tries to outdo her classmates in academics."
"The new model of the car outdoes its predecessors in fuel efficiency."
"Her kindness and generosity cannot be outdone."

Lists.name: stunning
Lists.meaning: is an adjective that is used to describe something that is extremely impressive, beautiful, or striking in appearance.
example: "She wore a stunning dress to the party."
"The view from the mountaintop was absolutely stunning."
"The sunset was so stunning that everyone stopped to admire it."

Lists.name: bask
Lists.meaning:
Enjoying Warmth:
To lie in and enjoy warmth, especially from the sun.
To take pleasure in a particular situation or condition.
example: "She loved to bask in the sun on the beach."
"He basked in the applause after his performance."
"They basked in the glory of their victory."

Lists.name: chuffed
Lists.meaning:
Pleased, delighted, or satisfied about something.
Feeling proud or gratified.
example: "She was absolutely chuffed with her exam results."
"He was chuffed to receive recognition for his hard work."
"They were chuffed to have won the competition."

Lists.name: charm
Lists.meaning:
Meaning:
A quality or feature that delights or attracts people; charisma.
An object believed to bring good luck or ward off evil.
To attract or delight someone with one's personality, manner, or behavior.
example: "She has a natural charm that makes everyone feel comfortable."
"His wit and humor were part of his charm."

Lists.name: pricks
Lists.meaning:
A sharp, sudden pain or sensation felt on the skin or inside the body.

A derogatory term used to insult someone, referring to them as irritating or unpleasant.

To make a small hole or wound in something by piercing or poking.
example: "He felt a prick on his finger when he touched the thorn."
"Don't be such a prick; nobody likes your attitude."
"The tailor pricks the fabric with pins to mark the measurements."

Lists.name: gross
Lists.meaning:
Earned or Generated (Revenue):
In financial or business contexts, "grossed" refers to the total amount of money earned or generated before any deductions or expenses are subtracted.
It indicates the total revenue or income generated from a particular source.
example: "The movie grossed over $100 million at the box office."
"Their annual sales grossed more than $1 million last year."

Lists.name: smear
Lists.meaning:
To spread or rub something (especially a liquid or oily substance) over a surface in a thin, uneven layer.
To cover or soil something with a substance, often in a careless or messy way.
To damage someone's reputation by making false accusations or spreading negative information.
example: "She smeared butter on her toast."
"The tabloid smeared the celebrity's name with scandalous stories."
"There was a smear of ketchup on his shirt."

Lists.name: greasy
Lists.meaning:
Literal:
Covered with or containing an oily substance.
Figurative:
Describing someone who is excessively flattering or insincere, often to gain favor.
example: "The mechanic's hands were greasy after working on the car."
"I don't trust him; he seems a bit greasy with his compliments."

Lists.name: get ahold
Lists.meaning:
To Contact or Reach Someone:

To make contact with someone, usually by phone or other communication methods.
To Obtain or Acquire Something:

To successfully get possession of or gain access to something.
To Gain Control of Something:

To take control or manage something effectively.
example: "I've been trying to get ahold of you all day."
"I finally got ahold of that book you recommended."
"He needs to get ahold of his emotions."

Lists.name: liability
Lists.meaning:
Legal/Financial Obligation:

A legal responsibility for something, especially the obligation to pay money to settle a debt or compensate for a loss.
Any amount owed by a business, organization, or individual, recorded on the balance sheet as debts or obligations.
Disadvantage/Risk:

A person or thing whose presence or behavior is likely to cause embarrassment or put one at a disadvantage.

Lists.name: bender
Lists.meaning:
Noun (Slang):

A long period of heavy drinking or drug use.
In some contexts, particularly in British slang, it can refer to a homosexual person, though this usage is derogatory and offensive.
Noun:

Objects or devices that bend something else, such as a metal bender used in construction.
example: "He went on a three-day bender after hearing the bad news."
"After finals, the students went on a bender to celebrate."
"They used pipe benders to shape the metal for the construction project."

Lists.name: trigger
Lists.meaning:
To cause an event or situation to happen or exist.
To activate or set off a mechanism or process.
Experiencing a strong emotional reaction, often negative, due to a specific stimulus or event that reminds one of past trauma or stress.
example: "The alarm was triggered by a movement in the house."
"His comments triggered an angry response from the audience."

Lists.name: get past
Lists.meaning:
To Move Beyond Something Physically:

To go around, over, or through an obstacle or barrier.
To Overcome or Deal With an Obstacle or Challenge:

To successfully handle or move beyond a problem, difficulty, or emotional hurdle.
To Be Accepted or Approved:

To gain acceptance or approval from someone or some authority.
example: "Can you help me get past this crowd?"
"It took her a long time to get past the loss of her pet."
"He managed to get past the security with his new ID card."

Lists.name: cut to the chase
Lists.meaning:
Idiom:
To get to the point or essential part of something without delay.
To skip the preliminaries or unnecessary details and focus on what's important.
example: "Let's cut to the chase and discuss the main issue."

Lists.name: grow a pair
Lists.meaning:
(slang)To summon courage or assertiveness, especially in a situation where someone is perceived as being timid or indecisive.
Implies a challenge to exhibit strength or resilience.
example: "Stop complaining and grow a pair!"
"She told him to grow a pair and stand up for himself."

Lists.name: hump
Lists.meaning:
A rounded protuberance found on the back of some animals, notably camels.
A small raised area or mound on a surface.
(Verb) To lift or carry something heavy.
example: The camel's hump stores fat, which can be converted to water and energy when food is scarce.
That guy is such a hump!
There was a small hump in the road that made the car bounce.

Lists.name: go through
Lists.meaning:
To experience or undergo a difficult or unpleasant situation.
To search or examine something carefully.
To be officially approved or completed.
example: Every morning, she went through her mail over a cup of coffee.
Her family drinks so much milk that they go through two gallons a week.
If United don't lose by more than 2 goals, they should go through to the next round.
I don't think my instant messages are going through.

Lists.name: screw
Lists.meaning:
(Verb) Past tense of "screw" - to fasten or tighten with a screw or similar device.
(Informal) To be in a difficult or problematic situation.
example: He screwed the shelf securely to the wall.
After missing the deadline, he realized he was completely screwed.

Lists.name: bing
Lists.meaning:
Prison solitary confinement, a term used by inmates.
(mostly Scotland) A slag heap, i.e. a man-made mound or heap formed with the waste material (slag) as a by-product of coal mining or the shale oil industry. Can also refer to the waste by-product from a foundry or furnace, formed into such a mound.
(mostly Scotland) A heap or pile.
example: We picked fresh Bing cherries from the orchard.
I used Bing to find information about the local events.

Lists.name: walk out
Lists.meaning:
(Phrasal verb) To leave abruptly or without prior notice, especially as a form of protest or disagreement.
(Phrasal verb) To suddenly stop working or functioning properly.
example: The employees decided to walk out of the meeting in protest.
The machine walked out halfway through the production process.

Lists.name: ever  since
Lists.meaning:
Continuously from a specified time in the past until the present.
From a particular event or point in time, indicating that something has been true or the case since then.
example: Ever since she moved to the city, she has loved the hustle and bustle.
Ever since he lost his job, he's been struggling to make ends meet.

Lists.name: upbeat
Lists.meaning:
Cheerful and optimistic.
The accented pulse or count in a musical measure.
example: She has an upbeat personality that brightens everyone's day.
The song's upbeat rhythm made everyone want to dance.

Lists.name: come out
Lists.meaning:
(Phrasal verb) To exit or emerge from a place or situation.
(Phrasal verb) To be released or become available to the public, especially books, movies, or new products.
(Phrasal verb) To reveal or disclose information, feelings, or one's true identity.
example: The cat finally came out from under the bed.
The new model of the phone is expected to come out next month.
She decided to come out to her family about her plans to move abroad.

Lists.name: slow down
Lists.meaning:
(Phrasal verb) To decrease speed or reduce the rate of movement.
(Phrasal verb) To relax, take it easy, or calm down.
example: He asked the driver to slow down because they were approaching a sharp turn.
After a hectic day, she needed to slow down and unwind.

Lists.name: ball up
Lists.meaning:
Phrasal verb) To make a mess of something; to confuse or complicate a situation.
(Phrasal verb) To crumple or twist something into a ball shape.
example: She really balled up the presentation by forgetting her notes.
He balled up the piece of paper and threw it into the trash.

Lists.name: fullfed
Lists.meaning:
(Verb) To make something (especially fabric or feathers) soft, light, or fluffy by shaking, beating, or similar action.
(Verb) To fail at something due to nervousness or lack of skill; to make a mistake.
example: She fluffed the pillows before guests arrived.
He fluffed his lines during the play and had to start over.

Lists.name: be through
Lists.meaning:
(Phrasal verb) To have finished or completed something.
(Phrasal verb) To have experienced something fully or to the point of exhaustion.
example: She is through with her homework.
She was through with her homework yesterday.
She is going through her homework right now
She has been through her homework many times.

Lists.name: twirly
Lists.meaning:
(Adjective) Characterized by twisting or spiraling movement; having a swirling or whirling motion.
(Informal) Something that is playful, lively, or whimsical.
example: She wore a twirly dress that spun around when she danced.
The children loved the twirly slides at the playground.

Lists.name: go down
Lists.meaning: To happen or take place, especially in a particular way
example: The meeting went down as planned.

Lists.name: take off
Lists.meaning:
(Phrasal verb) To remove something, especially clothing.
(Phrasal verb) To leave the ground and begin to fly (for airplanes, birds, etc.).
(Phrasal verb) To become successful or popular quickly.
(Phrasal verb) To leave a place suddenly.
example: He took off his jacket when he entered the warm room.
The plane took off at exactly 9:00 AM.
Her new business took off faster than she expected.
After the meeting, she took off without saying goodbye.

Lists.name: take heat off
Lists.meaning:
(Phrasal verb) To reduce pressure, stress, or criticism from someone or something.
(Phrasal verb) To divert attention or scrutiny away from someone or something.
example: The new scandal took the heat off the company's recent financial troubles.
He made a joke to take the heat off his friend during the meeting.

Lists.name: run into
Lists.meaning:
(Phrasal verb) To meet someone unexpectedly.
(Phrasal verb) To encounter a problem or difficulty.
(Phrasal verb) To collide with something.
example: I ran into an old friend at the grocery store yesterda
We ran into some technical issues during the presentation.
She ran into a parked car while trying to avoid a pedestrian.

Lists.name: waitress
Lists.meaning: (Noun) A female server who takes orders and serves food and drinks to customers in a restaurant or café.
example: The waitress took our orders with a smile.
She worked as a waitress during college to pay for her tuition.
antonyms: patron (in the context of a restaurant)

Lists.name: steer
Lists.meaning:
(Verb) To guide or control the direction of a vehicle, animal, or situation.
(Noun) A young male cattle that has been castrated and is raised for beef.
example: He carefully steered the car through the narrow streets.
The farmer raised steers for their meat.

Lists.name: steer clear
Lists.meaning: To avoid someone or something deliberately.
example: He decided to steer clear of the argument to avoid any trouble.
It's best to steer clear of that area at night.

Lists.name: gag
Lists.meaning:
(Verb) Choking or retching, often due to something unpleasant or offensive.
(Verb) Restraining or silencing someone forcibly or illegally.
example: She was gagging from the smell of the rotten eggs.
The government was accused of gagging the press during the crisis.

Lists.name: tan
Lists.meaning:
(Noun) The darkening of the skin due to exposure to the sun's ultraviolet rays.
(Verb) To darken or color skin by exposure to the sun or artificial ultraviolet light.
example: She got a nice tan after spending a week at the beach.
He loves to tan by the pool during the summer.

Lists.name: wind up
Lists.meaning:
To end up; to arrive or result.
To conclude, complete, or finish.
To find oneself in a particular situation unexpectedly.
example: I followed the signs, and I wound up getting nowhere.
Even though he had bad news, he tried to wind up his speech on a positive note.
We wound up our meeting earlier than expected.
Try not to wind up the kids too much right before bedtime.
He never planned to work in the tech industry, but he wound up managing a startup.

Lists.name: well up
Lists.meaning: To fill with tears, emotions, or fluid in a gradual or sudden manner, often indicating an emotional response.
example: She felt her eyes welling up with tears when she heard the sad news
His voice started welling up with emotion as he spoke about his grandmother.

Lists.name: crushions the blow
Lists.meaning: To lessen the impact or severity of bad news, criticism, or a difficult situation by providing some form of comfort or preparation
example: His manager praised his efforts before delivering the bad news to cushion the blow of the layoff.
They offered a small bonus to cushion the blow of the pay cut.

Lists.name: herd
Lists.meaning:
(Noun) A large group of animals, especially hoofed mammals, that are kept or move together.
(Verb) To gather and move or drive (animals) in a herd.
example: The cowboys herded the cattle into the pen.
The shepherd led his herd of sheep across the field.

Lists.name: deaf
Lists.meaning:
(Adjective) Lacking the ability to hear, either fully or partially.
(Adjective) Unwilling or unable to hear or listen; unresponsive.
example: He was born deaf and uses sign language to communicate.
She was deaf to his pleas for help.

Lists.name: foam
Lists.meaning: A mass of small bubbles formed on or in liquid, typically by agitation or fermentation processes.
example: The top of the cappuccino was covered with a thick layer of foam.
The mattress is made of memory foam for added comfort.
The ocean waves foamed as they crashed against the shore.

Lists.name: wipe
Lists.meaning:
(Verb) To rub something lightly with a cloth or one's hand to clean or dry it.
(Verb) To remove or eliminate something completely.
example: She wiped the table clean after dinner.
The rain wiped away the chalk drawings on the sidewalk.

Lists.name: steam
Lists.meaning:
(Verb) To cook food using the vapor produced by boiling water.
(Verb) To become angry or irritated (informal usage).
example: She steamed the vegetables for a healthier meal.
He was so steamed after the argument that he couldn't focus on work.

Lists.name: dent
Lists.meaning:
(Verb) Past tense of "dent": to make a small hollow mark in the surface of something by hitting or pressing it.
(Adjective) Having a small hollow mark on the surface.
example: He accidentally dented the car door when he backed into a pole.
The dented can was still safe to use, but it didn't look very appealing.

Lists.name: bring down
Lists.meaning:
(Phrasal verb) To reduce or lower something.
(Phrasal verb) To cause someone or something to fall or collapse.
(Phrasal verb) To cause a decrease in someone's mood or to make someone feel sad or depressed.
example: They worked hard to bring down the cost of production.
The protesters aimed to bring down the corrupt government.
The news of the layoffs really brought down the team's spirits.

Lists.name: stun
Lists.meaning:
(Adjective) Extremely impressive or attractive.

(Adjective) Shocking or surprising in a way that has a strong effect
example: The view from the mountaintop was absolutely stunning.
The news of the sudden resignation was stunning to everyone at the company.

Lists.name: tinkle
Lists.meaning:
(Verb) To make a light, clear, ringing sound.
(Noun) A light, clear, ringing sound.
(Verb, informal) To urinate (especially used for small children).
example: The glasses tinkled together as they were placed on the table.
The butler tinkled dinner.

Lists.name: just for the hell of it
Lists.meaning: To do something for no particular reason, just for fun or out of curiosity, often without caring about the consequences.
example: They decided to take a road trip just for the hell of it, with no specific destination in mind.
He pulled a prank on his friend just for the hell of it.

Lists.name: slide
Lists.meaning:
(Verb) Moving smoothly along a surface while maintaining continuous contact with it.
(Adjective) Describing something that can slide or is designed to slide.
example: The children were sliding down the hill on their sleds.
The sliding doors in the house save a lot of space.

Lists.name: attachments
Lists.meaning:
Noun: The action or process of attaching something.
Noun: A strong emotional bond or connection to someone or something.
Noun: Additional parts or equipment that can be connected to a main device or machine to enhance its functionality.
Noun: Files that are added to an email message for sending to another person.
example: The attachments of the new cabinet were sturdy and easy to install.
She felt a deep attachment to her childhood home.
The vacuum cleaner came with several attachments for different cleaning tasks.
Please check the email attachments for the report and the presentation.

Lists.name: fan out
Lists.meaning:
Verb: To spread out or disperse over a wide area, often in a shape resembling a fan.
Verb: To extend or arrange something to spread out in a fan shape.
example: Verb: She fanned out the cards on the table to show the variety of designs.
Verb: The police officers fanned out across the park to search for the missing child.

Lists.name: scratch
Lists.meaning:
To cut, scrape, or wear away the surface of something with a sharp or rough object.
A mark or wound made by scratching.
example: Be careful not to scratch the paint on the car.
He scratched his arm where the mosquito had bitten him.
She had to scratch her name from the list due to illness.
There was a deep scratch on the wooden table.
The dog's incessant scratching was a sign of fleas.

Lists.name: raggedy
Lists.meaning: Scruffy, shabby, or tattered in appearance; resembling rags or something worn out.
example: The old doll was raggedy, with patches missing from its clothes.
He wore a raggedy shirt that looked like it had seen better days.

Lists.name: coaster
Lists.meaning:
Noun: A small mat or tray on which a drink can be placed to protect the surface beneath it from heat, moisture, or scratches.
Noun: A small vehicle, typically on rails, used for amusement rides that travel at high speeds and often include drops and turns.
example: She placed her coffee mug on a coaster to prevent the table from getting stained.
The roller coaster at the amusement park was thrilling and had many loops.

Lists.name: inch
Lists.meaning: Moving very slowly or gradually in small increments, often describing a slow and deliberate movement forward.
example: The car inched forward in the traffic jam.
She was inching closer to the finish line in the race.

Lists.name: clench
Lists.meaning:
Verb: Holding something tightly or gripping firmly, often with force.
Verb: To close or tighten one's teeth and jaw muscles strongly, often due to stress, anger, or determination.
example: She was clenching her fists in frustration.
He clenched his teeth to control his anger.

Lists.name: crappy
Lists.meaning: Of poor quality; unpleasant or unsatisfactory.
example: The hotel room was small and had crappy furniture.
She had a crappy day at work due to a series of mishaps.

Lists.name: strew
Lists.meaning: To scatter or spread things untidily over a surface or area.
example: Leaves were strewn all over the garden after the storm.
The papers were strewn across the desk.

Lists.name: righteous
Lists.meaning:
(Adjective) Morally right or justifiable; virtuous.
(Adjective) Acting in accordance with divine or moral law; upright.
example: He was known for his righteous behavior and always stood up for what was right.
righteous indignation
Human beings should take a righteous path, and so should art. We should promote kindness and beauty through art.

Lists.name: reveries
Lists.meaning:
(Noun) Daydreams or fantasies; pleasant thoughts that distract one's attention away from the present.
(Noun) Musical compositions that are dreamy, imaginative, or fanciful in nature.
example: She often drifted off into reveries about traveling to far-off lands.
The pianist's latest album is filled with beautiful reveries that transport the listener to another world.

Lists.name: cogs
Lists.meaning:
(Noun) Toothed wheels that interlock with each other to transmit power or motion between moving parts in a machine.
(Noun) Figuratively used to refer to components or elements within a larger system that work together to achieve a particular result.
example: The cogs in the watch mechanism turn smoothly to keep accurate time.
Each department in the company is like a cog in the wheel, contributing to the overall success of the business.

Lists.name: Get Trampled
Lists.meaning:
Verb phrase: To be stepped on heavily and repeatedly, often causing injury or damage.
Verb phrase: To be figuratively overwhelmed or oppressed by a force or situation.
example: The spectators feared they might get trampled in the rush towards the stage.
In the corporate world, it's easy to get trampled if you don't stand up for yourself.

Lists.name: narrow
Lists.meaning:
Adjective: Having a small width in relation to length; limited in extent, amount, or scope.
Verb: To make or become less wide; to limit or restrict.
example: The alleyway was too narrow for the truck to pass through.
They won the match by a narrow margin.
The path begins to narrow as you approach the bridge.
We need to narrow our options before making a final decision.

Lists.name: shrink
Lists.meaning:
A psychiatrist or psychotherapist.
To cause to become smaller.
To become smaller; to contract..
To withdraw or retire, as from danger.
To move back or away, especially because of fear or disgust.
example: She wanted to help but shrank from the sight of blood.
My shrink said that he was an enabler, bad for me.
The dryer shrank my sweater.
This garment will shrink when wet.

Lists.name: couch
Lists.meaning:
Noun: A long upholstered piece of furniture for several people to sit on.
Verb: To express something in a particular way.
example: She lay down on the couch to watch TV.
He couched his criticism in very diplomatic terms.

Lists.name: put over
Lists.meaning:
To state, or explain a concept in a clear, understandable manner.
To delay or postpone something.
example: We decided to put over the project until next month.
Professor Jones is a good teacher. He knows how to put his ideas over to the students.

Lists.name: brag
Lists.meaning: To boast; to talk with excessive pride about what one has, is able to do, or has done; often as an attempt to popularize oneself.
example: He likes to brag about his new car.
Her constant brags about her grades annoyed her friends.

Lists.name: out of whack
Lists.meaning:
Not functioning properly; broken or malfunctioning.
Not in a proper state or condition; out of order.
example: The printer is out of whack again.
My sleep schedule has been out of whack since the time change.

Lists.name: threat
Lists.meaning:
A statement or indication of an intention to inflict pain, harm, or damage.
A person or thing likely to cause damage or danger
example: The email contained a threat to her safety.
Climate change is a significant threat to biodiversity.

Lists.name: heave
Lists.meaning:
To lift or haul something heavy with great effort.
An act of lifting or hauling.
example: They heaved the heavy box onto the truck.
She heaved a sigh of relief.
The ship heaved in the rough sea.
He heaved the ball across the field.

Lists.name: hop out
Lists.meaning: To exit or leave a place or vehicle quickly and lightly, often with a small jump or bound.
example: She hopped out of the car as soon as it stopped.
The cat hopped out of the window and onto the grass.

Lists.name: fold
Lists.meaning:
To bend something flexible and relatively flat over on itself so that one part of it covers another.
To bring an end to or collapse an operation or event.
example: She folded the letter and put it in the envelope.
The small company had to fold due to financial difficulties.
He carefully ironed out the folds in the fabric.
They welcomed her into the fold as a new team member.

Lists.name: sore
Lists.meaning: Areas of the skin that are painful and often red, broken, or infected.
example: He had several sores on his feet from wearing tight shoes.
The patient complained of sores in her mouth.

Lists.name: come out
Lists.meaning: to emerge appear from a enclosed place
example: she came out of his room before she finished his homework
The actress made her debut in the new movie's come out.

Lists.name: come over
Lists.meaning: to move o visiting to a specific place, often implying a visit o change of position.
example: can you come over to my house tonight?
A feeling of relaxion came over her as she listened to the music
I apologise for my behaviour last night. I don't know what came over me.

Lists.name: come through
Lists.meaning:
to succeed or achieve something despiste the obstacles or difficulties.
to fulfill  a promise or obligation
example: Despite the challenges, she came through with flying colors.
he promesed to help, and he came through when her need him most

Lists.name: Count on
Lists.meaning: To rely or depend on someone or something
example: You can count on me to help you with the project.
She counted on his support during the difficult time.
They counted on the weather to be good for the outdoor event.
He counted on his experience to guide him through the challenge.
We're counting on your expertise to solve the problem.

Lists.name: cut back
Lists.meaning:
To reduce the amount of (something).
To reduce spending.
To reduce consumption.
To perform the cutback maneuver.
example: We need to cut back heavily on office supplies. Is there another vendor we can use?
He needs to cut back on doughnuts. He weighs 289 pounds!

Lists.name: cut down
Lists.meaning:
To bring down by cutting.
To insult, to belittle.
To reduce the amount of something.
To slay, often in great numbers.
example: They want to cut down several trees to make room for the parking lot.
He wants to cut down on extra steps.

Lists.name: cut down on
Lists.meaning: to reduce the amount of something ,tipicaly comsumption or use a resource
example: the doctor adviced her to cut down on  sugar
we need to cut down on resources due to we are out of money .

Lists.name: cut off
Lists.meaning:
To remove via cutting.
To isolate or remove from contact.
To stop providing funds to (someone).
To end abruptly.
To interrupt (someone speaking).
example: he cut off a piece of rope
His parents cut him off to encourage him to find a job.
My phone call was cut off before I could get the information.
That dingbat cut me off as I was about to conclude my thesis.

Lists.name: cut out
Lists.meaning:
to stop doing something,especially a bad habit.
to exclude or remove something.
(Informal) To stop functioning (used for machines or engines).
example: she cut out the article of newpapper.
she needs to cut out smooking
The engine suddenly cut out on the highway.

Lists.name: drop in
Lists.meaning: To visit someone informally and usually without an appointment.
example: why don`t you drop in for a cofee sometime ?
she decided to drop in her friend while she was in  town

Lists.name: Dry out
Lists.meaning: To remove moisture or become dry
example: Leave the wet towels outside to dry out in the sun.
After the flood, the basement took weeks to dry out completely.
The paint will dry out faster if you leave the windows open.

Lists.name: Dry up
Lists.meaning: To cease or become scarce, often referring to resources
example: The river dried up during the drought.
Funding for the project dried up unexpectedly.
The well has dried up, leaving the village without water.
Job opportunities in the area have dried up recently.
The market for that product has dried up in recent years.

Lists.name: Fall off
Lists.meaning: To decrease or decline sharply in amount, quality, or intensity
example: Sales tend to fall off during the off-season.
Her performance fell off after she became ill.
The number of applicants fell off dramatically this year.
Interest in the project fell off as it progressed.
His enthusiasm for the hobby fell off over time.

Lists.name: Fall over
Lists.meaning: To lose balance and collapse to the ground
example: The chair wasn't stable and she fell over.
He slipped on the wet floor and fell over.
The toddler was running too fast and fell over.

Lists.name: Feel up to
Lists.meaning: To feel capable or prepared to do something
example: I'm not feeling up to going out tonight; maybe next time.
She didn't feel up to taking on the extra workload.
Do you feel up to running the marathon this weekend?

Lists.name: Get back at
Lists.meaning: To take revenge or retaliate against someone
example: She got back at him for the prank he played on her.
He got back at his rival by outperforming him in the competition.

Lists.name: Get by
Lists.meaning: To manage to survive or cope with a situation, especially with limited resources
example: She gets by on a small income by budgeting carefully.
They're just getting by until they find a new job.
He got by with the help of his friends during tough times.
The family is struggling to get by on one income.
We can get by with what we have for now.

Lists.name: Get on
Lists.meaning: To board or enter a vehicle or a mode of transportation
example: She got on the bus and found a seat near the window.
They got on the subway at the busy station.
He got on his bike and started pedaling.
The passengers got on the ferry to the island.
We need to get on the train before it departs.

Lists.name: Get out of
Lists.meaning: To avoid doing something that one should do; to escape a situation or obligation
example: He tried to get out of attending the meeting.
She got out of paying the fine by proving her innocence.

Lists.name: Get over
Lists.meaning: To recover from something, such as an illness or emotional setback
example: She's trying to get over a bad breakup.
He got over his cold quickly with rest and medication.
They're getting over the shock of the accident.
It takes time to get over the loss of a loved one.
We need to get over our fear of failure and move forward.

Lists.name: hello
Lists.meaning:
"Hello!" or an equivalent greeting.
To greet with "hello".
A greeting (salutation) said when meeting someone or acknowledging someone’s arrival or presence.
A greeting used when answering the telephone.
A call for response if it is not clear if anyone is present or listening, or if a telephone conversation may have been disconnected.
Used sarcastically to imply that the person addressed or referred to has done something the speaker or writer considers to be foolish.
An expression of puzzlement or discovery.

Lists.name: Allow for
Lists.meaning: To take into consideration or make provision for something
example: We need to allow for potential delays in our project timeline.
The budget allows for unexpected expenses.
You should allow for some flexibility in your schedule.
The design of the building allowed for future expansion.
The contract allows for termination under certain conditions.

Lists.name: Talk over
Lists.meaning: To discuss something with someone in order to reach a decision or agreement.
example: They need to talk over the details of the contract before signing it.
She talked over her concerns with her supervisor.
Let's talk over the options before making a decision.
They talked over the phone for hours.
It's important to talk things over before taking action.

Lists.name: word
Lists.meaning:
The smallest unit of language that has a particular meaning and can be expressed by itself; the smallest discrete, meaningful unit of language. (contrast morpheme.)
Something like such a unit of language:
The fact or act of speaking, as opposed to taking action. .
Something that someone said; a comment, utterance; speech.
A watchword or rallying cry, a verbal signal (even when consisting of multiple words).
A proverb or motto.
News; tidings (used without an article).
An order; a request or instruction; an expression of will.
A promise; an oath or guarantee.
A brief discussion or conversation.
(in the plural) See words.
(sometimes Word) Communication from God; the message of the Christian gospel; the Bible, Scripture.
(sometimes Word) Logos, Christ.
To say or write (something) using particular words; to phrase (something).
To flatter with words, to cajole.
To ply or overpower with words.
To conjure with a word.
To speak, to use words; to converse, to discourse.
Truth, indeed, that is the truth! The shortened form of the statement "My word is my bond."
(stereotypically) An abbreviated form of word up; a statement of the acknowledgment of fact with a hint of nonchalant approval.

Lists.name: inch
Lists.meaning:
A unit of length equal to one twelfth of a foot, or exactly 2.54 centimetres.
The amount of water which would cover a surface to the depth of an inch, used as a measurement of rainfall.
The amount of an alcoholic beverage which would fill a glass or bottle to the depth of an inch.
A very short distance.
(followed by a preposition) To advance very slowly, or by a small amount (in a particular direction).
To drive by inches, or small degrees.
To deal out by inches; to give sparingly.

Lists.name: rub
Lists.meaning:
The act of applying pressure and friction to a surface, often using a back-and-forth motion.

The act of rubbing.
An impression of a design or texture made by placing paper over it and rubbing with a pencil, charcoal, or other marking material.
example: She was rubbing her sore shoulder.
The rubbing of the chair legs on the floor was annoying.
She made a rubbing of the ancient inscription.

Lists.name: commit
Lists.meaning:
Verb:
To pledge or bind to a certain course or policy.
To carry out or perpetrate (a mistake, crime, or immoral act).
Adjective:
Dedicated or loyal to a cause, activity, or job; wholeheartedly dedicated.
example: He committed to finishing the project on time.
She committed a serious error in the report.
She is a committed teacher who works tirelessly for her students.
They are committed to their community service efforts.

Lists.name: sicken
Lists.meaning:
To make ill.
To become ill.
To fill with disgust or abhorrence.
.
example: The news of the disaster was sickening.
The smell of the spoiled food was sickening.
The constant motion of the boat was sickening him.
She is sickening with the flu and needs to rest.

Lists.name: hideous
Lists.meaning: Extremely ugly or unpleasant; horrifying.
example: The old building had a hideous appearance after years of neglect.
The movie’s monster was so hideous that it was hard to look at.

Lists.name: come at last
Lists.meaning: To finally arrive or achieve something after a long period of waiting or effort.
example: After years of hard work, her big break came at last when she was offered the lead role in a film.
The long-awaited package came at last, and she was thrilled to finally receive it.

Lists.name: chalk
Lists.meaning:
A soft, white, powdery limestone consisting mainly of fossil shells of foraminifers.
A substance (often colored) used for writing or drawing on blackboards or other surfaces.
(Informal) To attribute something to a particular cause.
example: The teacher wrote the lesson on the blackboard with white chalk.
The cliffs of Dover are made of chalk.
She chalked a message on the sidewalk.
He chalked his success up to hard work and determination

Lists.name: off the cuff
Lists.meaning:
To denote something done spontaneously or without preparation.
In cycling, it can refer to a rider falling behind the main group.
example: In the cycling race, he was struggling and eventually fell off the back.
She gave an impressive speech right off the back, with no notes.

Lists.name: nag
Lists.meaning:
Adjective:
Persistently worrying or discomforting.
Continuously reminding or complaining.
Noun:
The act of persistently urging or complaining.
Verb (gerund):
Continuously urging or complaining in a way that is irritating.
example: She had a nagging feeling that she had forgotten something important.
His nagging cough kept him up all night.
His constant nagging about the chores was driving her crazy.
She is always nagging him to take out the trash.

Lists.name: board
Lists.meaning:
Having a wide distance from side to side; wide.
Covering a large number and wide scope of subjects or areas.
General; not detailed.
Including a large number of things or people.
example: The river was broad and difficult to cross.
She has broad knowledge in various subjects.

Lists.name: lead off
Lists.meaning:
To start or begin something, especially an event, series, or performance.
To be the first in a sequence or list.
example: The keynote speaker will lead off the conference with an inspiring speech.
she led off the meeting with a brief introduction.
His lead-off was strong, setting the tone for the rest of the debate.

Lists.name: blister
Lists.meaning:
Adjective:
Extremely intense or severe.
Very hot.
Very fast or forceful.
Verb (Gerund/Present Participle of "blister"):
Causing a blister or blisters.
Becoming covered with blisters.
example: he athletes ran at a blistering pace.
he criticism she received was blistering.
The sun was blistering hot that afternoon.
Her new shoes were blistering her feet.

Lists.name: scanty
Lists.meaning:
Insufficient in quantity or amount: Not enough to meet the needs or expectations.
Sparse or meager: Very limited or minimal in extent.
example: The information provided was scanty and did not cover all the necessary details.
They had a scanty supply of resources for the project.
The scanty clothing was not suitable for the cold weather.
The evidence was scanty, making it difficult to reach a conclusion.

Lists.name: dire
Lists.meaning: Extremely serious or urgent; warning of disaster.
example: The news reported a dire warning about the impending storm.
They are in dire need of assistance after the earthquake.

Lists.name: pal
Lists.meaning: A close friend.
example: I've known him since we were kids; he's my best pal.
She went to the movies with a group of her pals.
He palled around with his classmates.

Lists.name: lousy
example: "The movie was really lousy; I wouldn't recommend it."
"She had a lousy day at work and was in a bad mood."
"He felt lousy after catching a cold."

Lists.name: fit
Lists.meaning:
Adjective:

Suitable or appropriate for a particular purpose or situation.
Noun:

The process of trying on clothes to see if they fit properly.
A small part or accessory used to connect or adjust larger parts, often in plumbing, electrical work, or construction.
The act of making something fit or suitable.
Verb (present participle/gerund of "fit"):

The act of trying on clothes or making adjustments to ensure proper fit.
Making something suitable or appropriate for a particular purpose.
example: "It is fitting to wear formal attire to the wedding."
"She went for a dress fitting before the big event."
"The plumber installed new fittings in the bathroom."
"The fitting of the new parts took several hours."
"She is fitting the dress to ensure it looks perfect."

Lists.name: swell
Lists.meaning:
Verb:

To increase in size or volume, typically due to internal pressure: This can happen due to injury, infection, or other conditions.
To become larger or rounder in size: Often used to describe body parts.
To rise or expand: Used metaphorically to describe an increase in quantity, volume, or intensity.
example: "Her ankle began to swell after she twisted it."
"Pride swelled within him as he received the award."
"The river swelled after the heavy rain."
"There was a swell in the crowd as more people arrived."
"Surfers waited for the next big swell."
"The swell on his forehead was noticeable after he hit his head."
"We had a swell time at the party last night."

Lists.name: floss
Lists.meaning:
Verb:

To clean between the teeth using dental floss: A method of oral hygiene.
To show off or boast (slang): Often used in the context of displaying wealth, skills, or other attributes.

Noun (slang):

The act of showing off or boasting: Displaying one's possessions, wealth, or status in a conspicuous way.
example: "She is flossing her teeth after every meal."
"He was flossing his new car at the party."
"His constant flossing about his new job is getting annoying."

Lists.name: sport
Lists.meaning: To wear or display something with a sense of pride: Often used informally to describe showing off an item or a style.
example: "He sported a new jacket at the party."

Lists.name: pity
Lists.meaning:
Noun:

Sympathy and sorrow for someone else's misfortune: An emotional response to the suffering or misfortune of others, often accompanied by a desire to help or alleviate their distress.
A cause for regret or disappointment: Something that is regrettable or unfortunate.
Verb:

To feel sympathy or sorrow for someone: To express or experience compassion or concern for someone else's suffering or misfortune.
To express regret or disappointment about something: Used less frequently in this sense.
example: "She felt a deep pity for the homeless man on the street."
"He pitied the children who lost their home in the fire."

Lists.name: lift up
Lists.meaning:
To raise something or someone to a higher position.
To inspire or encourage someone.
example: She asked him to help lift up the heavy box.
The crane can lift up to 20 tons.

Lists.name: ditzy
Lists.meaning: Silly, scatterbrained, or frivolous, often used to describe someone who is not very serious or who is forgetful and careless.
example: She can be a bit ditzy at times, always forgetting where she left her keys.
Despite her ditzy demeanor, she is actually very intelligent.

Lists.name: cut some slack
Lists.meaning: To allow someone more freedom or leniency than usual; to be less critical or to show mercy.
example: I know he was late to the meeting, but cut him some slack; he's been under a lot of stress lately.
She’s been working extra hours, so let’s cut her some slack if she’s a bit behind on her tasks.

Lists.name: leap
Lists.meaning:
(Verb) The act of jumping or springing a considerable distance or height.
(Adjective) Describing something that is characterized by jumping or moving quickly and energetically.
example: The cat was leaping from one rooftop to another with ease.
The leaping salmon were a spectacular sight in the river.

Lists.name: trigger
Lists.meaning:
Noun:

A device that initiates an action: Often used in the context of firearms to denote the lever that, when pulled, releases the firing mechanism.
An event or situation that causes a reaction: Can refer to something that sets off a particular course of action, emotion, or series of events.
Verb:

To cause an event or situation to happen: To initiate or provoke a reaction or series of events.
example: "He pulled the trigger and the gun fired."
"The announcement was the trigger for widespread protests."
"The news triggered a wave of panic among investors."
"Certain smells can trigger memories from childhood."

Lists.name: tilt
Lists.meaning:
Verb:

To cause to slope or incline: To move or place something so that it is not straight or level.
To lean or cause to lean in a particular direction: Often used to describe the act of leaning to one side.
Noun:

A sloping position or movement: The state of being tilted or the act of tilting.
An inclination or bias: Sometimes used metaphorically to describe a tendency or preference towards a particular point of view or attitude.
example: "He tilted the chair back and relaxed."
"The picture on the wall is slightly tilted."
"The table has a slight tilt to it."
"The tilt of the Earth's axis affects the seasons."

Lists.name: smitten
Lists.meaning:
Deeply in love or infatuated: Strongly attracted to someone or something.
Affected by something overwhelming: Sometimes used more broadly to describe being strongly affected by a particular feeling or emotion.
example: "He was smitten with her the moment they met."
"She is smitten by the charm of the old town."

Lists.name: napkin
Lists.meaning:
A piece of cloth or paper used at meals: For wiping the mouth and fingers while eating.
A piece of cloth or paper used for cleanliness: Can also be used for various purposes, such as wrapping or cleaning.
example: "She placed a napkin on her lap before starting to eat."
"Please pass me a napkin; I spilled some juice."

Lists.name: point up
Lists.meaning: To emphasize or highlight something: To make something more noticeable or clear.
example: "The teacher pointed up the key concepts that would be on the test."
"This incident points up the need for better safety measures."

Lists.name: neat
Lists.meaning:
Tidy and orderly: Arranged in a clean, organized, and aesthetically pleasing manner.
Well-executed: Done with precision and skill.
Unadulterated: Referring to a drink, typically an alcoholic one, served without ice or mixers.
Excellent or pleasing: Informal usage to describe something that is very good or enjoyable.
example: "Her desk was always neat and organized."
"His handwriting is very neat."
"He prefers his whiskey neat."
"He thought the new gadget was pretty neat."

Lists.name: starting from square one
Lists.meaning: Beginning again from the very beginning, often after a previous attempt has failed
example: After the project was rejected, we had to start from square one.
The experiment didn't work, so the scientists went back to square one.

Lists.name: sip
Lists.meaning: To drink (a liquid) by taking small mouthfuls.
example: She sipped her tea slowly, savoring the flavor.
He took a sip of water before continuing his speech.

Lists.name: tear off
Lists.meaning: To remove or detach something by ripping or pulling it away forcefully
example: She tore off the wrapping paper to reveal the gift inside.
The athlete tore off his shirt in celebration after winning the game.

Lists.name: alley
Lists.meaning: A narrow passageway between or behind buildings, often used as a shortcut or for service access.
example: The kids played basketball in the alley behind their house.
He took a shortcut through a dark alley to get home faster.

Lists.name: rough
Lists.meaning:
Having an uneven or irregular surface; not smooth or level.
Difficult or unpleasant; not gentle or kind.
Approximate or imprecise.
example: The road was rough and bumpy, making the ride uncomfortable.
She had a rough day at work and was looking forward to relaxing at home.
He gave a rough estimate of the project's cost

Lists.name: Leave out
Lists.meaning: To exclude someone or something
example: He felt hurt when they left him out of the game.
Don't leave out any important details in your report.
They left out the most interesting part of the story.

Lists.name: beneath
Lists.meaning:
Preposition:

At a lower level or position than something else.
Under or below something in a physical or metaphorical sense.
Adverb:

In or to a lower place or position.
example: The cat slept beneath the table to stay out of sight.
The submarine traveled beneath the surface of the water.
The roots grew beneath the foundation of the house.

Lists.name: as in
Lists.meaning:
Used to introduce an example or clarification of something previously mentioned.
