Indicates a comparison or similarity to something that has been referenced.
example: Her job is challenging, as in working long hours and dealing with difficult clients.
The policy is strict, as in not allowing any exceptions.
He plays the guitar, as in similar to how a professional musician would.
The project needs to be detailed, as in how a high-quality report would be.

Lists.name: moisten
Lists.meaning:
The act of making something slightly wet or damp.
To add a small amount of liquid to something to prevent it from becoming dry.
example: She was moistening the soil in the garden to help the plants grow.
The recipe calls for moistening the dough with a bit of water.
The lotion is designed for moisturizing and moistening dry skin.
He used a spray bottle for moistening the cake before frosting it.

Lists.name: smush
Lists.meaning:
To crush or squash something, often with a soft, gentle force.
To press or squeeze something together until it becomes deformed or flattened.
example: She accidentally smushed the cookies when she packed them in her bag.
The kids smushed the clay into a flat shape.
He smushed the leftover food into a small container to save space in the refrigerator.
The pillow was smushed under the weight of the heavy books.

Lists.name: Fix up
Lists.meaning: To repair, arrange, or improve something
example: They fixed up the old house and turned it into a cozy home.
She fixed up the garden for the party.
He fixed up the car and got it running again.
We need to fix up the office before the clients arrive.
They fixed up the website to make it more user-friendly.

Lists.name: Follow up
Lists.meaning: To pursue or take further action on something previously initiated
example: She followed up on her job application with a phone call.
They followed up the meeting with a detailed email.
He followed up the sales pitch with a personalized offer.
The doctor followed up the surgery with regular check-ups.
We need to follow up on the customer complaints to ensure satisfaction.

Lists.name: Get around to
Lists.meaning: To finally find time to do something that one has intended to do for some time
example: I'll get around to cleaning the garage this weekend.
She finally got around to reading that book.

Lists.name: Give in
Lists.meaning: To surrender or yield to pressure or persuasion
example: She finally gave in to his demands.
They gave in to temptation and ate the cake.
He gave in to peer pressure and joined the group.
The government gave in to protesters' demands.
I refuse to give in to fear and will continue fighting for what's right.

Lists.name: Go along with
Lists.meaning: To agree or comply with someone or something
example: She decided to go along with the group's decision.
They went along with the plan even though they had reservations.
He went along with his friend's suggestion for dinner.
The employees went along with the new policy without much resistance.
I'll go along with your proposal if it makes sense.

Lists.name: Go by
Lists.meaning: To pass or move past
example: As the years go by, we become wiser.
A car went by at high speed.
Don't let the opportunity go by.

Lists.name: Go off
Lists.meaning: To explode, make a sudden loud noise, or stop working
example: The alarm clock went off at 6 AM.
The fireworks went off with a bang.
The car alarm went off in the middle of the night.
The lights went off during the storm.
The bomb went off in the city center.

Lists.name: Go over
Lists.meaning: To review, examine, or discuss something in detail
example: She went over the details of the project with her team.
They need to go over the contract before signing it.
He went over his notes before the exam.
The teacher went over the lesson to ensure everyone understood.
Let's go over the plan one more time to make sure it's perfect.

Lists.name: Hand back
Lists.meaning: To return something to someone
example: Please hand back the documents after reviewing them.
She handed back the keys to the owner.
He handed back the book he borrowed.

Lists.name: Grow out of
Lists.meaning: To become too large for something or to stop having an interest in something as one matures
example: He grew out of his clothes so quickly.
She grew out of her childhood hobbies.
The baby has grown out of her crib.

Lists.name: Hang on
Lists.meaning: To wait for a short time or to hold tightly
example: Hang on a minute, I need to grab my coat.
He hung on to the rope tightly.
Hang on, I'll be right with you.

Lists.name: Head back
Lists.meaning: To return to a place
example: It's getting late, we should head back home.
They headed back to the office after lunch.
I'm heading back to my hometown this weekend.

Lists.name: Head for
Lists.meaning: To go towards a particular place
example: They're heading for the mountains this weekend.
We should head for the exit before the crowd gets too big.
After work, he headed for the gym.

Lists.name: Hit on
Lists.meaning: To flirt with someone in a direct or obvious way
example: He was hitting on every woman at the bar.
She felt uncomfortable when he hit on her at work.
They laughed off his attempts to hit on them.
The guy at the party kept hitting on everyone.
I don't appreciate being hit on by strangers.

Lists.name: Hold against
Lists.meaning: To bear a grudge or resentment towards someone
example: She held his mistake against him for years.
Don't hold it against me if I can't make it to the meeting.
He held their past argument against her.

Lists.name: Keep down
Lists.meaning: To control or suppress something, such as noise, costs, or emotions
example: She tried to keep down her excitement when she received the good news.
They installed soundproofing to keep down the noise from the busy street.
He kept down expenses by cutting unnecessary spending.
The medication helped keep down the symptoms of the illness.
We need to keep down our carbon emissions to protect the environment.

Lists.name: Keep from
Lists.meaning: To prevent someone from doing something or to avoid doing something
example: She kept him from making a big mistake.
He couldn't keep from laughing during the serious meeting.
The rain kept us from going outside.

Lists.name: Keep off
Lists.meaning: To stay away from or avoid something
example: They kept off the grass to avoid damaging it.
She kept off social media during her exam preparation.
He kept off junk food to maintain a healthy diet.
The children were told to keep off the road while playing.
We should keep off topics that might cause arguments.

Lists.name: Knock over
Lists.meaning: To accidentally tip or push something over
example: She knocked over a vase while dusting the shelves.
They knocked over the glass of water with their elbow.
He knocked over a stack of books reaching for the top shelf.
The wind knocked over the trash cans on the street.
We need to be careful not to knock over any fragile items.

Lists.name: Leave out
Lists.meaning: To exclude someone or something
example: He felt hurt when they left him out of the game.
Don't leave out any important details in your report.
They left out the most interesting part of the story.

Lists.name: easy in
Lists.meaning:
The process of starting something slowly and gently to make a transition smoother or to reduce the impact of a change

Gradually acclimating to a new situation, routine, or activity.
example: "We’re easing in to the new software with a training period before full implementation."
"She spent the first week easing in to her new job to get used to the different pace and responsibilities."

Lists.name: ruffle
Lists.meaning:
To disturb or disarrange something, typically a surface or appearance, often creating a disordered or uneven state.
Verb (Emotional): To irritate or upset someone.
Noun: A frill or decorative pleat, typically on clothing, that creates a ruffled effect.
example: "The wind ruffled the pages of the book."
"Her comments ruffled his composure."
The dress had a beautiful ruffle along the hemline."

Lists.name: sweat
Lists.meaning:
Noun: A clear, salty liquid produced by the sweat glands in the skin, typically in response to heat, exercise, or stress.
Verb: To excrete sweat from the body; also used figuratively to describe effort or anxiety.
example: "She wiped the sweat from her forehead after the intense workout."
"He began to sweat heavily as he ran up the hill."

Lists.name: pull off
Lists.meaning:
To Achieve or Accomplish:

To successfully complete or achieve something, especially when it is difficult or challenging.
To Remove or Take Off:

To physically take something off or remove it, usually from a surface or position.
To Drive Away:

To maneuver a vehicle away from a place, typically starting from a stop or parked position.
example: She managed to pull off the complex project despite the tight deadline.
They pulled off an impressive victory against a tough opponent.
He pulled off the bandage gently to avoid causing pain.
The artist pulled off the painting from the wall to examine it closely.
After finishing their stop, they pulled off and continued down the road.
The car pulled off the shoulder of the highway and back into traffic.

Lists.name: breezy
Lists.meaning:
Characterized by a light wind: Describing a situation where there is a gentle, pleasant wind.
Casual or carefree: Used to describe a relaxed or unconcerned attitude or manner.
Airy or well-ventilated: Describing a space that is cool and has a good flow of fresh air.
example: It was a breezy day at the beach, perfect for a walk along the shore.
Her breezy attitude made her very approachable and easy to talk to.
Despite the tight deadline, he maintained a breezy demeanor.
The breezy porch was a lovely place to sit and relax during the summer.

Lists.name: jaunty
Lists.meaning: Having or expressing a lively, cheerful, and self-confident manner.
example: He wore a jaunty outfit that was all the rage.
He walked down the street with a jaunty swaggering step, as if daring others less perfectly satisfied to intrude upon his good mood.

Lists.name: dip in
Lists.meaning:
To Immerse Briefly: To briefly put a part of something into a liquid or other substance, often quickly and then remove it. This can refer to dipping an object or body part into a liquid.

To Make a Quick Involvement: To become briefly involved in an activity or situation, often without a long-term commitment or extensive engagement.

To Take a Small Amount: In the context of using a resource or consuming something, it can mean to take a small portion or sample from a larger amoun
example: "She dipped her brush in the paint before starting her artwork."
"He quickly dipped his toes in the water to check the temperature."
"He decided to dip in and out of the meeting due to other commitments."
"I’m just going to dip in to see what the discussion is about."
"I’ll just dip in a little bit of the sauce to taste it."

Lists.name: dwarve
Lists.meaning: Small People: Historically, "dwarves" could also refer to people with dwarfism, though contemporary language prefers "people with dwarfism" or "little people" as more respectful terms.
example: "The story included a band of dwarves who embarked on a quest to reclaim their homeland."

Lists.name: trip out
Lists.meaning: To Become Distracted or Overwhelmed: Sometimes used to describe becoming overly engrossed or overwhelmed by something, leading to confusion or distraction.
example: "He really tripped out on that new VR game; it felt like he was in another world."
"She tripped out after taking the psychedelic drug and had vivid hallucinations."
"I tripped out when I saw the long list of tasks I had to complete."
"He trips out over every little detail, making it hard to focus on the bigger picture."

Lists.name: patch thorugh
Lists.meaning:
Telecommunications:

Connecting a Call: To connect a phone call or communication from one line to another. This is often used in the context of phone systems where a call is transferred from an operator or intermediary to the intended recipient.
General Use:

Facilitate Communication: To enable or facilitate communication between parties, especially when initially routed through an intermediary
example: "Can you patch me through to Mr. Smith's office?"
"The operator will patch the call through once you provide the extension number."
"The assistant patched through the important information to the manager."

Lists.name: aloof
Lists.meaning:
Distant or Detached: Describes someone who is emotionally or physically distant, showing a lack of interest or involvement in interactions with others. It implies a sense of detachment or indifference.
Unapproachable: Characterized by a lack of friendliness or warmth, often creating a barrier between oneself and others.
example: Despite being at the party, she remained aloof, standing in the corner and not engaging in conversations.
His aloof demeanor made it difficult for others to approach him.
The manager’s aloof attitude discouraged employees from sharing their concerns.
She came across as aloof because she rarely made eye contact or smiled.

Lists.name: tablecloth
Lists.meaning: Cloth for Covering a Table: A piece of fabric used to cover the surface of a table, typically for protection, decoration, or to enhance the dining experience. It is often spread over the table before meals or special events.
example: She placed a white tablecloth on the dining table for the dinner party.
The tablecloth had a festive pattern for the holiday celebration.

Lists.name: break even
Lists.meaning:
To Reach a Financial Point of No Profit or Loss:

Verb Phrase: To cover all costs and expenses with no net gain or loss, essentially reaching a point where income equals expenditure.
To Recover Costs:

Verb Phrase: To reach a financial status where the total revenue matches the total costs, making neither a profit nor a loss.
example: The business finally broke even after several months of losses.
After selling 100 units, the startup was able to break even on its initial investment.
The event organizers hoped to break even by selling enough tickets to cover the venue costs.

Lists.name: carry away
Lists.meaning:
To Take Something or Someone to Another Location:

Verb Phrase: To physically transport or move something or someone from one place to another.

Lists.name: restrain

Lists.name: cuddle

Lists.name: walk though

Lists.name: batch

Lists.name: Let in

Lists.name: Pull off

Lists.name: Put back

Lists.name: Stick out

Lists.name: shrug off
Lists.meaning:
To dismiss or ignore something, especially a problem or criticism, as unimportant or irrelevant.
To recover quickly from an illness, injury, or negative experience
example: He tried to shrug off the criticism and focus on his work.
She shrugged off the cold and went to work anyway.
Despite the setback, the team managed to shrug off their disappointment and win the next game.

Lists.name: nag
Lists.meaning:
Adjective:
Persistently worrying or discomforting.
Continuously reminding or complaining.
Noun:
The act of persistently urging or complaining.
Verb (gerund):
Continuously urging or complaining in a way that is irritating.
example: She had a nagging feeling that she had forgotten something important.
His nagging cough kept him up all night.
His constant nagging about the chores was driving her crazy.
She is always nagging him to take out the trash.

Lists.name: headway
Lists.meaning: refers to progress or movement toward a goal or objective. It is often used to describe making significant advancements or improvements, especially in a challenging situation.
example: The team is finally making headway on the project after weeks of delays.
Despite the obstacles, they made considerable headway in negotiations.

Lists.name: lean
Lists.meaning:
To incline, bend, or rest against something for support; to rely on someone or something for help.

 Describing something or someone with little fat, thin; also used to describe something that is lacking in richness, substance, or quantity.
example: She leaned on the fence while watching the sunset.
He always leans on his friends for advice.
The athlete has a lean body due to rigorous training.
It was a lean year for the company, with profits down significantly.

Lists.name: pick on
Lists.meaning: means to repeatedly criticize, tease, or bully someone, often unfairly or in a way that makes them feel bad.
example: The older kids used to pick on him because he was smaller.
She feels like her boss is always picking on her for minor mistakes.

Lists.name: fill in for
Lists.meaning: "Fill in for" someone means to temporarily take the place or responsibilities of another person, especially at work or in a specific role.
example: Can you fill in for me at the meeting tomorrow?
She had to fill in for her colleague who was out sick.

Lists.name: warm
Lists.meaning: can describe a moderately high temperature, typically one that is comfortable or pleasant. It can also refer to someone or something that is friendly, affectionate, or enthusiastic.
example: The room feels warm and cozy.
She warmed the soup on the stove.
He gave her a warm smile.

Lists.name: lay into
Lists.meaning: "To lay into" someone means to criticize or attack them harshly, either verbally or physically.
example: The coach laid into the players for their poor performance in the game.
She laid into her colleague after he missed another deadline.

Lists.name: smooth
Lists.meaning:
Smooth as an adjective refers to a surface without roughness, bumps, or irregularities.
It can also describe something that is easy, effortless, or without interruptions (e.g., a smooth process).
As a verb, it means to make something flat, even, or free of roughness.
example: The table had a smooth finish, with no scratches or dents.
They had a smooth journey, with no traffic or delays.
She smoothed out the wrinkles on her dress before leaving.

Lists.name: reharse
Lists.meaning:
Rehearse means to practice or prepare for a performance, speech, or event by going through it multiple times.
It can also refer to mentally preparing or planning something by reviewing or repeating it.
example: The actors rehearse their lines every day to ensure a flawless performance.
She rehearsed her presentation several times before the big meeting.

Lists.name: mere
Lists.meaning:
Mere is an adjective that emphasizes something that is considered to be nothing more than what it appears to be. It often conveys a sense of insignificance or minimalism.
It can also refer to something that is simply or only something, without any additional value or significance.
example: The mere thought of failure was enough to discourage him from trying.
She was a mere child at the time, with no understanding of the complexities involved.

Lists.name: thereafter
Lists.meaning: Thereafter is an adverb that refers to the time period following a specific event or point in time. It means "after that" or "subsequently."
example: She graduated from college and, thereafter, moved to a new city for work.
The company was acquired in 2020 and, thereafter, expanded its operations internationally.

Lists.name: despise
Lists.meaning:
Despised is the past tense of despise and means to regard someone or something with intense dislike or contempt.
It can also indicate a strong feeling of scorn or hatred towards a person or thing.
example: He despised the unfair treatment he received at work.
The politician was despised by many for his controversial statements.

Lists.name: detach
Lists.meaning:
Detached means not attached or separated from something, often referring to physical separation.
It can also describe a state of emotional or social detachment, where someone is uninvolved or indifferent.
example: The garage is detached from the main house.
He seemed detached during the meeting, not showing any emotion or interest.

Lists.name: oath
Lists.meaning:
An oath is a solemn promise or declaration, often invoking a divine witness, regarding one's future action or behavior.
It can also refer to a formal pledge or vow, such as one made during legal proceedings or ceremonies.
example: He took an oath to uphold the Constitution.
The witness was asked to swear an oath before testifying in court.

Lists.name: rave
Lists.meaning:
refers to speaking or writing about something with great enthusiasm or admiration.
It can also mean to talk wildly or incoherently, as if one is delirious or insane.
example: She raved about the amazing food at the new restaurant.
The man raved about conspiracy theories, making little sense.

Lists.name: embody
Lists.meaning:
To represent or express something abstract in tangible form.
To include or contain something as a constituent part.
To be an example of a particular quality or idea.
example: The statue embodies the spirit of freedom.
Her actions embody the values of our community.
The new policy embodies the government's commitment to environmental sustainability.

Lists.name: raging
Lists.meaning:
Characterized by violent or uncontrollable anger, emotions, or actions.
Marked by intense or widespread activity or movement.
example: The raging bull charged at the matador.
Her eyes showed a raging fury at the betrayal.
The river turned into a raging torrent after the heavy rainfall.

Lists.name: thriving
Lists.meaning: Prosperous and growing; flourishing.
example: The city's economy is thriving due to new investments.
The garden is thriving thanks to regular watering and care.
Despite the challenges, their business is thriving.

Lists.name: step up
Lists.meaning:
To increase the amount, speed, or intensity of something.
To take action or responsibility, especially when others are hesitant to do so.
To come forward or volunteer for a role or task.
example: The company plans to step up production to meet the high demand.

Lists.name: settler
Lists.meaning: People who move to a new area or country to live and establish a community, often in a region that is sparsely populated or uninhabited.
example: The early settlers faced many hardships in the New World.
The settlers built homes and farms in the remote valley.
European settlers arrived in America seeking freedom and land.

Lists.name: shrouded
Lists.meaning:
Covered or concealed as if with a shroud.
Enveloped in darkness, mystery, or secrecy.
example: The mountain was shrouded in mist.
The room was shrouded in darkness after the power outage.
The details of the plan were shrouded in secrecy.

Lists.name: slip past
Lists.meaning:
To move or pass by someone or something quietly or unnoticed.
To avoid detection or capture by moving stealthily or quickly.
example: The spy managed to slip past the guards undetected.
She tried to slip past her parents to avoid their questions.
I nearly missed the deadline, but I managed to slip past it just in time.

Lists.name: gist
Lists.meaning: The main or essential part of a matter; the essence or central idea.
example: She didn't go into details but gave me the gist of the story
I missed the beginning of the meeting, but I got the gist of what was discussed.
The gist of his argument was that we need to invest more in renewable energy.

Lists.name: sweep off
Lists.meaning:
To clean or clear a surface by brushing away dirt, debris, or dust.
To carry someone off their feet, typically in a romantic or exciting way.
example: She used a broom to sweep off the porch.
He swept her off her feet with his charming smile and kind words.

Lists.name: slip
Lists.meaning:
As a Verb:

Meaning:

To slide unintentionally for a short distance, typically losing one's balance or footing.
To move quietly and smoothly, often to avoid being noticed.
To pass or go by smoothly or easily.
To make a small mistake.
example: Be careful not to slip on the icy pavement
She slipped out of the room without anyone noticing.
Time seems to slip away when you're having fun.

Lists.name: grueling
Lists.meaning: Extremely tiring and demanding; requiring a lot of effort and endurance.
example: The marathon was a grueling test of endurance.
She faced a grueling schedule at work this week.

Lists.name: onwards
Lists.meaning:
1. In a continuing forward direction; ahead.
2. From a particular time forward.
example: We traveled onwards, eager to reach our destination.
From this day onwards, I promise to work harder.
